                    <outline text="Mobile Combiner Techniques #h1">
                        <outline text="In this study in order to reconstuct polynomial $$f$$ and obtaining the value of secret, the following interpolation methods is been used:"/>
                        <outline text="Lagrange Interpolation :">
                            <outline text="Consider shares $$s_i=(x_i,f(x_i))$$"/>
                            <outline text="Polynomial $$f(x)$$ of order k interpolates $$f(x_i)$$ at points $$x_i$$ and can be given as $$f(x)=\sum^k_{i=1} f(x_i)l_i(x)\;(\bmod p)$$ where $$l_i(x)={\prod_{j=1, j\neq k}^k(x-x_j)}/{\prod_{j=1, j\neq k}^k(x_i-x_j)}\;(\bmod p)$$ with properties of $$l_i(x_j)=1$$, when $$ i=j$$ and $$ l_i(x_j)=0$$, when $$i\neq   j$$"/>
                            <outline text="Following Shamir's scheme, the secret $$s$$ can be obtained as $$ s =f (0)$$ and using the above interpolation, $$s= \sum^k_{i=1} f(x_i)l_i(0)$$ where $$l_i(0)={\prod_{j=1, j\neq k}^k(-x_j)}/{\prod_{j=1, j\neq k}^k(x_i-x_j)}\;\pmod p$$"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Deficiencies of Lagrange Interpolation are:">
                            <outline text="1. calculating $$l_i$$ for each point requires $$O(n^2)$$ operations"/>
                            <outline text="2. Adding a new point is requires a new computation of $$l_i$$ from scracth."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Improved Lagrange Interpolation: The above interpolation can be improved in such way that the calculating $$l_i$$ for each point requires only $$O(n)$$ operations. This method is called &quot;Improved Lagrange Interpolation&quot;.  This method can be described briefly as follows:">
                            <outline text="Consider shares $$s_i=(x_i,f(x_i))$$"/>
                            <outline text="Define $$l(x)=(x-x_1)(x-x_2)\cdots(x-x_k)\pmod  p$$ and $$w_i=1/\prod_{j=1. i\neq j}^k(x_i-x_j)$$    $$(mod p)$$"/>
                            <outline text="Hence $$f(x)=\sum^k_{i=1} f(x_i)l(x) w_i/(x-x_i)$$        $$(mod p)$$"/>
                            <outline text="Similarly the secret $$s$$ can be obtained as $$s= l(0)\sum^k_{i=1} -f(x_i)w_i/x_i$$   $$(mod p)$$. Here adding new point does require evaluating $$l(0)$$ and $$w_i$$ for a new data but only requires $$O(n)$$ operations. And the secret can be easly evaluated once the values of $$l(0)$$ and $$w_i$$ are known."/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Description of Barycentric Interpolation: the above interpolation can be modified further to improve the running time of obtaining the value of the secret, $$s$$. ">
                            <outline text="Consider shares $$s_i=(x_i,f(x_i))$$ where no $$x_i$$ are the same, and $$i=1...k$$"/>
                            <outline text="Following the above method, the polynomial $$f(x) $$ of order $$k-1$$ interpolates $$f(x_i)$$ at points $$x_i$$  can be written as $$f(x)=l(x)\sum^k_{i=1}f(x_i)\frac{ w_i}{\overline{(x-x_i)}} $$        $$(mod p)$$ #jc fraction notation not consistent with previous one"/>
                            <outline text="Furthermore, $$\sum_{i=1}^k l_i(x) = 1$$ #jc I did not get this step. "/>
                            <outline text="Hence $$1=l(x)\sum^k_{i=1}\frac{ w_i}{\overline{(x-x_i)}} $$  #jc I did not get this step. Dividing $$f(x)$$ by this equation gives:"/>
                            <outline text="  $$f(x)=\frac{\sum^k_{i=1}\frac{ w_i}{(x-x_i)} f(x_i)}{\overline{\sum^k_{i=1}\frac{ w_i}{\overline{(x-x_i)}}} }$$       $$(mod p)$$   where $$w_i$$ is defined as above and it is called Barycentric weights."/>
                            <outline text="Using the polynomial function $$f(x)$$ the secret $$s$$ can be obtained as  $$s=\sum^k_{i=1} f(x_i)\frac{{ w_i}/{(-x_i)}}{\overline{\sum^k_{i=1}{ w_i}/{(-x_i)}} }$$       $$(mod p)$$  "/>
                            <outline text="Hence the secret can be computed in two steps:">
<outline text="The first step is the evaluation of the values of $$Qi=\frac{{ w_i}/{(-x_i)}}{\overline{\sum^k_{i=1}{ w_i}/{(-x_i)}} }$$ which can be evaluated with only the values of the first components of the shares, i.e. $$(x_{i1},x_{i2},...,x_{ik})$$  $$(mod p)$$"/>
<outline text="The second step is the sum of the products $${Q_i}\times{f(x_i)}$$"/>
                            </outline>
                            <outline text="In this study the results of the first step $$Qi$$, is saved, as attribute in the class of combining and can be re-used to combine other shares with the same values of $$x_i$$. The calculation of the $$Q_i$$is the process which takes the most of the running time during combining. #jc what is the calculation complexity? Better than $$O(n)$$ operations?"/>
                        </outline>
                        <outline text="Algorithm for Reconstructing a ssecret based on Shamir's method using Barycentric Interpolation???"/>
                        <outline text="RabinDispersal Algorithm and Combiner?? (maybe not)"/>
                    </outline>
